editorialNotes.standard: The line never ends at Dr. Panda’s Ice Cream Truck, and that’s just how our kids like it. They jump at the chance to whip up new flavours and serve sky-high sundaes piled with toppings. Watching customers gobble down their desserts cracks them up every time (and us too).

An utterly charming way to introduce young kids to music and animation, Loopimal is simple and powerful in a way that almost defies description. Kids arrange and rearrange tiles in sequences underneath a cute polar bear, octopus, and the like, triggering a series of musical tones mirrored by adorable dances from the animal gang. There are no goals and no consequences—just a safe place to learn, play, and laugh.

editorialNotes.standard: A lot of us live on this great big planet without really understanding what makes it tick. This kid-friendly introduction to the Earth’s inner and outer workings uses touch-based tools and exercises to teach everything from how volcanoes are formed to where rain comes from. With clear language, vivid photos, interactive 3D models and a delightful sandbox mode, it’s a fantastic owner’s manual for the world we live in.

editorialNotes.tagline: Interact with the power of nature
editorialNotes.standard: Part digital toy and part planetary handbook, The Earth gives kids insight into the workings of our world in a way that’s delightfully intuitive and fun. From rockslides to earthquakes to erupting volcanoes, these artful interactive dioramas respond to tapping and swiping with results that are both whimsical and educational. An accompanying guide for parents and teachers delves into the technical science behind all these phenomena, but kids can explore, experiment, and absorb earthly knowledge at their own pace.
